      "id": "urolanion-st.albans",
      "type": "Feature",
      "properties": {
        "description": "St.Albans is not the correct location of the Verulamium of the early British Saint Albanus and here's why. It always struck me as odd, reading Tacitus' account of the Boudicca rebellion of 60/61 that the Iceni should attack St.Albans when it is so far away from their homeland, and not a military base. But Tacitus says it was a castra called Verulamium.\r\n\r\nIn Ptolomy's Gegraphia he names Urolanion on the same latitude as Leicester, but further East. Bede's HEGA gives 3 names for this; Uerolamium, Uerlamacaestir and Uaeclingacaestir, indicating the present day Castor, on Ermine Street. The reason for the mistake occurred just over 1200 years ago when King Offa authorised the Benedictines to establish an abbey on the Watling Street. They knew from the Iter. Antonini that it was Verulamium, and from the recently produced and copied HEGA assumed the site of Albanus.  ",
        "location_precision": "precise",
        "title": "Urolanion-St.Albans",
        "link": "http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/79739/urolanion-st.albans"
      }
